{"ticker": "CCJ", "company": "CAMECO CORP", "weight_sum": 1.94, "etfs": ["ARKQ"], "is_private": false, "query": "($CCJ OR \"Cameco\") -is:retweet min_faves:10 since_time:1777754140 until_time:1777761643", "n_fetched": 2, "n_kept": 1, "n_dropped": 1, "kept": [{"type": "tweet", "id": "2050600260695675330", "url": "https://x.com/NicolasFlamelX/status/2050600260695675330", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/NicolasFlamelX/status/2050600260695675330", "text": "They probably don\u2019t include $GLXY because they\u2019re framing this as an \u201cAI power portfolio\u201d, not an \u201cAI data center real estate / compute infrastructure portfolio.\u201d\n\nGalaxy is more of a powered data center campus owner/developer through Helios. Most names on that list are either:\n\nPower generation \u2014 nuclear, renewables, grid electricity\nNuclear fuel supply chain \u2014 uranium, enrichment, HALEU\nData center power/cooling equipment\nEnergy storage / batteries\n\nSo the omission is not necessarily because they have \u201cmore GW than Galaxy.\u201d It is more likely because Galaxy is still mentally categorized by many people as crypto/financial services, while these names are already categorized as AI energy beneficiaries.\n\nThe key comparison\n\nGalaxy\u2019s Helios is actually very large.\n\nGalaxy says Helios now has over 1.6 GW of ERCOT-approved, utility-contracted power capacity after receiving approval for an additional 830 MW. Galaxy describes this as positioning Helios among the largest and fastest-growing data center developers in North America.  \n\nThat is not small. In fact, compared with many of these public \u201cAI power\u201d names, Galaxy has a more direct and tangible AI infrastructure asset than the market gives it credit for.\n\nBut the list is mixing very different types of companies.\n\nSo is Galaxy smaller than these?\n\nAgainst utilities/generators like NextEra or Constellation: yes, Galaxy is smaller.\n\nAgainst nuclear fuel names like Cameco, Centrus, Energy Fuels: it is not an apples-to-apples comparison. They don\u2019t \u201cown data center GW\u201d the way Galaxy owns Helios capacity exposure.\n\nAgainst future nuclear names like Oklo or NuScale: Galaxy arguably has something more immediate. Helios has approved/contracted utility capacity now, while many SMR/advanced nuclear stories are still about future deployment, permitting, commercialization, and long timelines.\n\nAgainst Vertiv/Tesla/Eos: again, different category. Those are equipment/storage plays. Galaxy is a site/power/data center campus play.\n\nMy read\n\nThe funny part is: Galaxy probably belongs on a broader AI power list more than some people realize.\n\nThe market still sees:\n\nGalaxy = crypto stock\n\nBut Helios makes the cleaner framing:\n\nGalaxy = scarce powered land + AI data center infrastructure + crypto operating leverage\n\nThat is why the omission is kind of the opportunity. It shows the narrative transition is still incomplete.", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 0, "replyCount": 1, "likeCount": 16, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 1215, "createdAt": "Sat May 02 15:36:15 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 2, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2050600260695675330", "displayTextRange": [0, 278], "inReplyToUserId": null, "inReplyToUsername": null, "author": {"type": "user", "userName": "NicolasFlamelX", "url": "https://x.com/NicolasFlamelX", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/NicolasFlamelX", "id": "951386802841145346", "name": "Nicolas Flamel", "isVerified": false, "isBlueVerified": true, "verifiedType": null, "profilePicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1456013254279450627/zr87V18s_normal.jpg", "coverPicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_banners/951386802841145346/1710282903", "description": "", "location": "", "followers": 61721, "following": 3761, "status": "", "canDm": true, "canMediaTag": false, "createdAt": "Thu Jan 11 09:34:24 +0000 2018", "entities": {"description": {"ur